Alma Levant Hayden, a chemist, joined the @NIH in the 1950s, and may have been the first African-American scientist at the FDA. In 1963, her work in Spectrophotometry helped improve safety of cancer treatments. #BlackHistoryMonth #BlackScientists #BlackStem pic.twitter.com/46JaQaTbvD

Percy Julian was one of the most influential chemist in American history. In 1935, he synthesized physostigmine to treat glaucoma. In the 1940s, he synthesized cortisone and hydrocortisone, impacting treatment of many ailments. He held over 130 patents. #BlackHistoryMonth pic.twitter.com/WcvAxJQcOS

Alice Augusta Ball was the first woman to graduate from the @uhmanoa , and the first person to successfully develop an injectable form of chaulmoogra oil to treat leprosy. Her work was published in the @J_A_C_S . #BlackHistoryMonth #BlackSTEM #BlackScientists #Mahalo pic.twitter.com/HLEJJnEeMX

Granville T. Woods held 60 patents, including one for inventing the multiplex telegraph, which allowed communication by voice over telegraph wires. He defeated Thomas Edison's claims to the patent, and went on to sell patents to Alexander Graham Bell & others. #BlackHistoryMonth pic.twitter.com/C5wxyoufmq

We're celebrating #BlackScientists and #BlackSTEM for #BlackHistoryMonth . In 1947, Marie Maynard Daly was the first African-American woman to earn a PhD in Chemistry in the US. She earned her degree @Columbia and is known for her work on amylase. pic.twitter.com/eJHRqwLGhO
